"a.使人悲伤的，阴沉的 【英】 adj. 使人悲伤的(showing sadness) 【例】 dismal weather, countryside adj. 阴沉的; 沮丧的; 忧郁的 【记】在中世纪的英国指不吉利的日子(dis = day, mal邪恶的, 坏的)dismay(使气馁)使你dismal 【记】dis + mal(不好，坏，反常)， dis 与mal都是否定及不好的意思，原指魔鬼或地狱般的日子，具足地狱的特点；已经学过的dism开头的，dismiss or dismay 都是使人沮丧的 dismal (adj.)  c.1400, from Anglo-French dismal (mid-13c.), from Old French (li) dis mals ""(the) bad days,"" from Medieval Latin dies mali ""evil or unlucky days"" (also called dies Ægyptiaci), from Latin dies ""days"" (see diurnal) + mali, plural of malus ""bad"" (see mal-). Through the Middle Ages, calendars marked two days of each month as unlucky, supposedly based on the ancient calculations of Egyptian astrologers (Jan. 1, 25; Feb. 4, 26; March 1, 28; April 10, 20; May 3, 25; June 10, 16; July 13, 22; Aug. 1, 30; Sept. 3, 21; Oct. 3, 22; Nov. 5, 28; Dec. 7, 22). Modern sense of ""gloomy, dreary"" first recorded in English 1590s, in reference to sounds. Related: Dismally."
